 and archivists from Germany, Finland, Scandinavia, the US, and the UK address urgent questions about environmental degradation, globalization, consumerism, and the role of new technologies of representation in relation to landscape. Wide-ranging case studies examine the interpretation, experience, and appropriation of landscape in northern Europe, Canada, northern England, Scotland, and the Nordic countries. The book explores tensions in landscape photography between an emphasis on proximity and the embodied experience of place and space, and an advocacy of distance and critical engagement and a questioning of the primacy of direct experience.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aLandscape photography. 4aAesthetics. 4aArt History. 4aFine Arts. 4aImage. 4aLandscape. 4aNorth. 4aSublime. 4aVisual Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh  aAesthetics.  aLandscape.  aNorth.  aSublime.1 aBird, Nicky, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCronin, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaly, Tim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldie, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldie, Chris, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHarvey, Aileen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHill, Tracy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aItälahti, Mikko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeister, Jessica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeck, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aQuelvennec, Lena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWhite, Darc